	<h1>
This Does Compute: Diving beneath the surface with AITS
</h1>
	<div class="page-title-hline">&nbsp;</div>
	










<!-- MAIN CONTENT AREA - START -->



		<div class="floatright">
			<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="sidebar" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_sidebar --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_sidebar --> <!-- InstanceEndEditable -->

<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Sidebar" --><!-- InstanceEndEditable --><br class="hide" />
			</div>


			<div class="contentcolumn">
				<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="maincontent" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_maincontent --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_maincontent -->

	<div id="entry-372">
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				
<img alt="Cover-sum11.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/Cover-sum11.jpg" class="mt-image-left" style="float: left; margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt;" width="220" height="331" />A ship sailing across turbulent seas, a hockey referee making sure the puck stays in play, an island in the ocean. These diverse images represent a vital component of Concordia's Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science: its Academic and Information Technology Services unit, or AITS. With more than 30 information technology professionals making up the core AITS team, it's not surprising that the unit can be seen in so many different lights. It's also fitting that the common thread behind these mental pictures is the idea that the most important work done by AITS is never seen.<br /><br />For Joel Krajden, Manager of Core Technologies, it's the metaphor of the ship that holds truest: "I see the users of the services we provide as being passengers on a ship travelling from point A to point B. While passengers order room service, they sail on unaware that in the hull of the ship are<br />the various teams that keep the boiler room, kitchen, radar and navigation system working -- and the ship oncourse." <br /><br />For Paul Gill, Associate Director of AITS, it's the hockey referee that best represents the group. "When you watch a great hockey game," he explains, "you aren't even aware of the ref. You don't know what his name is, you're barely aware of the calls he's making. You're just enjoying the play. But if the game gets sloppy and you notice bad calls and missed infractions, then you can't take your eyes off the ref! If we're doing our work right, then AITS is like the good ref. You're barely aware of us: you just know that everything's running smoothly."<br /><br />But it is perhaps the metaphor suggested by Anne Bennett, Senior Systems Administrator, which resonates loudest: AITS as a tropical island. The Faculty is solidly grounded on the sea floor and those who use the services provided by AITS are experiencing sunny weather up top. But the presence of threats below the surface of the water requires different teams to respond and provide services to users, while keeping the sharks at bay and ensuring the safety of those on dry land. <br /><br />For the better part of the past decade, this dedicated team of computer experts has worked tirelessly to ensure that the sun shines brightly on the island, meeting the diverse information technology needs of this Faculty with speed, efficiency, andquality. But its foundations were first formed some 30 years ago, at the dawn of personal computing.<br /><br />In 1980, the Department of Computer Science and Software Engineering was at the cutting edge of an evolving field. As personal computing soared in popularity, the department readily adapted by establishing a dedicated team whose mandate was to ensure day-to-day IT operations -- whether these involved faculty members, staff or students -- ran smoothly and stayed clear of sticky situations. The concept caught on.<br /><br />Soon, the other departments within the Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science had their own crews of IT professionals to keep computing facilities ticking along efficiently. This autonomous method of working remained in place throughout the 1990s but had to evolve quickly in the early 2000s, when a multi-million dollar grant was secured to establish a new home for Engineering: the state-of-the-art EV building. With all of the Faculty's departments set to converge under one roof, former Dean Dr. Nabil Esmail, decided that it would also make sense to merge the Faculty's IT resources.<br /><br />It was a massive undertaking. The various departments, centres, units, and institutes of the Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science were spread across the Sir George Williams campus, located in nearly 20 different buildings. Bringing them together meant more than just lifting desks and chairs, it meant assigning the right spaces to the right people, all while establishing a robust IT infrastructure that would ensure uninterrupted service when the<br />time to move finally came. The team that is now AITS had approximately two years to carefully plan the move while maintaining the high level of service to which users had become accustomed. Recalls Krajden, "Not only was there the question of the physical move and the desktop computers needing to be all in place, there was always the question of how are we going to do this in terms of all the servers that had to be moved into the EV building. Before we could even do that, we already had to have planned out what the network would look like."<br /><br />With kilometres of cables running from the 16th floor through to the subbasement, the IT backbone of the EV building is a high-tech web. "The first people to work in this building were the network folks," says Stan Swiercz, Manager of Information Systems. "They were here putting in the switches and taking care of the network as the building was being built around them." With over 3,000 end pieces of cables to be plugged into switches and 1,500 ports in this building alone, everything had to be meticulously planned in order to avoid total chaos. The fact that the AITS team got it right is a testament to the deep knowledge and impressive skill-sets possessed by all members.<br /><br />Paul Gill has a twinkle in his eye when he remembers what happened when it came time for moving day. "When staff and faculty members finally moved in," he recounts, "they walked to their offices and found a sign on the door telling them which jack to connect to. So they just plugged in and within minutes they were reading their email." <br /><br />On the surface of things, the weather on the AITS island has seemed sunny ever since to those above the water line. Below the surface and behind the scenes, however, the team's constant vigilance has been necessary to keep the Faculty's computing systems safe and secure. Threats like malware, phishing, and viruses are real and always evolving and the team is constantly monitoring services, performance, and the network itself to ensure everything is running smoothly. If you seldom see any spam in your Inbox, it's because you're protected by the AITS team. If your operating system has just been upgraded, it's because providing up-to-date tools is an important facet of maintaining the network's security... in short, if the hockey game is going smoothly, if the weather is nice and sunny, if you are sailing on calm seas, it's all because of Academic and Information Technology Services.<br /><div><br /></div>

			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
	
